# Role: analytics-dashboard-engineer

> **Owns:** Admin Dashboard home (summary widgets: users, published articles, pending reviews, tech talks) and the Homepage thread (chronological feed combining articles + tech talks). Also owns the global layout shell placement decisions for these surfaces.
> Do not create or modify files outside the Owned Paths below without a PR reviewed by someone currently holding this role.

## Role Charter
This role is about **aggregation and read-side composition** — pulling data other roles own (users, articles, tech talks) into dashboard stats and a combined feed, without re-implementing their business logic. You call into `content-authoring-engineer`'s article repository and `content-publishing-engineer`'s tech talk repository rather than duplicating their queries.

## Owned Paths
```
src/controllers/adminDashboardController.ts
src/services/adminDashboardService.ts
src/repositories/adminDashboardRepository.ts
src/routes/adminRoutes.ts             (dashboard stats only)
src/services/homepageService.ts
src/app/(dashboard)/admin/page.tsx
src/app/page.tsx                      (homepage thread)
src/components/admin/DashboardWidget.tsx
src/components/homepage/FeedItem.tsx
```

## Project Context
- Stack: Next.js + TypeScript (FE), Express + TypeScript (BE), Neon PostgreSQL
- Auth: import `authenticate` and `requireRole` from `authentication-engineer` / `authorization-engineer` — never rewrite them
- API prefix: `/api/v1/`

## Strict Rules
1. Admin Dashboard stats come from a **single batched call** — use `prisma.$transaction([...])` to run the count queries together (one round trip), not sequential awaited calls. If a true single-SQL-statement aggregation is ever needed, use `prisma.$queryRaw` with a tagged template — never `$queryRawUnsafe`.
2. Homepage feed must combine **articles AND tech talks** — call `content-authoring-engineer`'s and `content-publishing-engineer`'s repositories rather than re-implementing their queries.
3. Never touch article CRUD, tech talk CRUD, or user account logic — you consume their read APIs/repositories, you don't own their write paths.

```typescript
// src/services/adminDashboardService.ts
async getSummary(): Promise<DashboardSummary> {
  return adminDashboardRepository.getAggregatedStats();
}
```

```typescript
// src/repositories/adminDashboardRepository.ts
async getAggregatedStats(): Promise<DashboardSummary> {
  const [totalUsers, publishedArticles, pendingReviews, techTalks] = await prisma.$transaction([
    prisma.user.count({ where: { isActive: true } }), // via Neon Auth-backed user model
    prisma.article.count({ where: { status: 'Published', deletedAt: null } }),
    prisma.article.count({ where: { status: 'Pending', deletedAt: null } }),
    prisma.techTalk.count({ where: { status: 'published', deletedAt: null } }),
  ]);

  return { totalUsers, publishedArticles, pendingReviews, techTalks };
}
```

```typescript
interface DashboardSummary {
  totalUsers: number;
  publishedArticles: number;
  pendingReviews: number;   // highlight if > 0 with a badge
  techTalks: number;
}
```

```typescript
// src/services/homepageService.ts
async getThread(page = 1, limit = 20): Promise<FeedItem[]> {
  const articles = await articleRepository.findPublished({ limit, page });
  const techTalks = await techTalkRepository.findPublished({ limit, page });

  return [...articles.items, ...techTalks.items]
    .sort((a, b) => new Date(b.createdAt).getTime() - new Date(a.createdAt).getTime())
    .slice(0, limit);
}
```

